WEBVTT

0
00:00:03.029 --> 00:00:05.469
To understand why OCP matters today,

1
00:00:05.760 --> 00:00:08.859
you have to go back to the critical point that started it all.

2
00:00:09.829 --> 00:00:10.550
In 2010,

3
00:00:10.659 --> 00:00:12.229
the rise of mobile computing,

4
00:00:12.430 --> 00:00:13.170
social media,

5
00:00:13.390 --> 00:00:17.090
and cloud storage caused internet traffic to explode.

6
00:00:17.819 --> 00:00:20.479
But the hardware powering it was stuck in the past.

7
00:00:21.450 --> 00:00:22.750
In 2011,

8
00:00:23.170 --> 00:00:23.530
Meta,

9
00:00:23.729 --> 00:00:24.729
formerly Facebook,

10
00:00:24.930 --> 00:00:25.829
hit a wall.

11
00:00:26.170 --> 00:00:28.850
They were growing so fast that traditional data

12
00:00:28.850 --> 00:00:31.729
center technology literally could not keep up.

13
00:00:32.919 --> 00:00:34.759
They weren't just running out of space,

14
00:00:35.040 --> 00:00:38.180
they were burning power on things that didn't matter.

15
00:00:38.599 --> 00:00:39.439
At the time,

16
00:00:39.639 --> 00:00:41.220
every server was a black box.

17
00:00:42.369 --> 00:00:44.049
Proprietary designs,

18
00:00:44.250 --> 00:00:46.369
gratuitous plastic bezels,

19
00:00:46.490 --> 00:00:48.270
logos that blocked airflow,

20
00:00:48.729 --> 00:00:51.709
and power supplies that were horribly inefficient.

21
00:00:52.130 --> 00:00:53.229
If they wanted the scale,

22
00:00:53.569 --> 00:00:54.930
rules had to be broken.

23
00:00:55.819 --> 00:00:56.250
So,

24
00:00:56.419 --> 00:01:00.009
a small team of engineers at Facebook asked a radical question.

25
00:01:01.479 --> 00:01:05.879
What if we designed a data center like a single giant computer?

26
00:01:06.949 --> 00:01:06.959
What

27
00:01:07.790 --> 00:01:09.610
if we stripped away the vanity

28
00:01:09.750 --> 00:01:11.769
and focused only on efficiency?

29
00:01:12.760 --> 00:01:13.930
That question

30
00:01:14.180 --> 00:01:17.029
launched the Open Compute Project or OCP.

31
00:01:18.069 --> 00:01:22.440
OCP took the schematics for the most efficient server in the world,

32
00:01:22.709 --> 00:01:24.120
and we didn't patent them,

33
00:01:24.349 --> 00:01:25.389
we published them.

34
00:01:26.569 --> 00:01:29.290
We invited the world to hack our hardware.

35
00:01:30.699 --> 00:01:33.480
The result was the vanityre server.

36
00:01:34.169 --> 00:01:35.309
We removed the plastic,

37
00:01:35.559 --> 00:01:36.959
we centralized the power,

38
00:01:37.089 --> 00:01:38.690
we optimize the airflow.

39
00:01:38.930 --> 00:01:40.529
It wasn't just cheaper to build,

40
00:01:40.669 --> 00:01:43.250
it was 38% more efficient

41
00:01:43.410 --> 00:01:46.569
and 24% less expensive to run.

42
00:01:47.720 --> 00:01:50.260
This model works so well for a reason.

43
00:01:50.760 --> 00:01:52.680
The hyper scales run into the physical

44
00:01:52.680 --> 00:01:56.540
limits of IT infrastructure years before anyone else

45
00:01:56.919 --> 00:01:58.120
because of their size,

46
00:01:58.319 --> 00:01:59.550
scale operations,

47
00:01:59.760 --> 00:02:01.839
and relentless performing demands.

48
00:02:02.449 --> 00:02:02.970
Also,

49
00:02:03.129 --> 00:02:05.930
by solving these extreme scaling challenges with

50
00:02:05.930 --> 00:02:08.788
the industry and an open mindset first

51
00:02:08.919 --> 00:02:11.000
and then publishing those blueprints,

52
00:02:11.240 --> 00:02:15.449
we hand those engineer solutions directly to the rest of the market,

53
00:02:15.649 --> 00:02:17.149
accelerating adoption

54
00:02:17.330 --> 00:02:19.800
and driving new industry benchmarks.

55
00:02:20.199 --> 00:02:22.509
OCP is not a standards body itself,

56
00:02:22.850 --> 00:02:25.770
but by the nature of its open innovation engine,

57
00:02:26.000 --> 00:02:29.410
it supports and contributes to standardization.

58
00:02:30.619 --> 00:02:31.160
Today,

59
00:02:31.339 --> 00:02:33.660
OCP isn't just for hyper scales,

60
00:02:34.059 --> 00:02:38.160
it's a $132 billion ecosystem.

61
00:02:39.110 --> 00:02:41.600
From the co-location facility down the street

62
00:02:41.979 --> 00:02:43.759
to the edge of the telecom network,

63
00:02:44.139 --> 00:02:47.539
open hardware is the standard for high performance computing.

64
00:02:49.270 --> 00:02:50.800
But this isn't just history.

65
00:02:52.470 --> 00:02:53.899
With the rise of AI

66
00:02:54.080 --> 00:02:55.429
and heat dense workloads,

67
00:02:55.520 --> 00:02:58.000
the principles we established in 2011.

68
00:02:59.160 --> 00:03:00.309
Efficiency,

69
00:03:00.600 --> 00:03:01.440
openness,

70
00:03:01.919 --> 00:03:02.500
impact,

71
00:03:02.839 --> 00:03:03.190
skill,

72
00:03:03.320 --> 00:03:07.449
and sustainability are the only way we will survive the next decade.

73
00:03:08.589 --> 00:03:10.029
So welcome to the community.

74
00:03:10.309 --> 00:03:11.669
Let's take a look at the specs.